# COMP3221 Assignment 1 – Routing Protocol

## Coding Environment

- Python 3.8+
- macOS / Linux (any POSIX-compatible system)
- Standard library only – no external packages required
  (uses: socket, threading, json, heapq, sys, time, os, abc)

## How to Run

    chmod +x Routing.sh
    ./Routing.sh <Node-ID> <Port-NO> <Node-Config-File> <RoutingDelay> <UpdateInterval>

Example:

    ./Routing.sh F 6005 Fconfig.txt 60 10

## Arguments

| Argument         | Description                                               |
|------------------|-----------------------------------------------------------|
| Node-ID          | Single uppercase letter (A–Z)                             |
| Port-NO          | Integer port the node listens on (starting from 6000)     |
| Node-Config-File | File listing immediate neighbours (see spec §3.2)         |
| RoutingDelay     | Seconds to wait before the first routing-table output     |
| UpdateInterval   | Seconds between periodic UPDATE broadcasts                |

## Project Structure

    Routing.sh                  Entry-point wrapper script
    README                      This file
    routing/
      __init__.py               Top-level package marker
      __main__.py               Allows `python3 -m routing`
      main.py                   CLI argument parsing and validation
      core/                     Core data structures & orchestration
        graph.py                  Undirected weighted graph (adjacency list)
        router.py                 Dijkstra shortest-path computation
        node.py                   Node class (orchestrator, threading)
      commands/                 Command pattern implementation
        base.py                   Abstract Command base class
        dynamic.py                CHANGE, FAIL, RECOVER, QUERY, RESET, …
        bonus.py                  MERGE, SPLIT, CYCLE DETECT
        factory.py                CommandFactory input parser
      network/                  Network communication layer
        socket_manager.py         UDP socket wrapper
        protocol.py               STDIN/STDOUT and socket message formats
      config/                   Configuration handling
        parser.py                 Config-file parser and validator
      utils/                    Shared helpers
        validation.py             Node-ID validation
        formatting.py             Cost formatting and error_exit

## Supported Commands

All commands from the spec are implemented:

| Command        | Description                                      |
|----------------|--------------------------------------------------|
| CHANGE         | Update the cost of an edge to a neighbour        |
| FAIL           | Mark a node as down (stop broadcasts if self)    |
| RECOVER        | Bring a node back up                             |
| QUERY          | Print least-cost path from this node             |
| QUERY PATH     | Print least-cost path between any two nodes      |
| RESET          | Restore original config and re-broadcast         |
| BATCH UPDATE   | Process a file of commands sequentially           |
| MERGE (bonus)  | Absorb one node into another                     |
| SPLIT (bonus)  | Partition the graph alphabetically                |
| CYCLE DETECT (bonus) | Report whether the graph contains a cycle   |

## Design Overview

The solution uses a link-state approach: each node shares its full known
topology with direct neighbours over UDP, so every node can eventually
learn the entire graph and run Dijkstra locally.

Four threads run concurrently:

1. Main / STDIN thread – reads commands and UPDATE packets.
2. Socket listener (daemon) – receives topology data from neighbours.
3. Sender (daemon) – broadcasts UPDATE packets every UpdateInterval seconds.
4. Routing calculator (daemon) – re-runs Dijkstra when topology changes.

Thread safety is ensured with an RLock on shared state and a separate lock
on print output to prevent interleaving.
